According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While traveling, 3 - 275g totes fell from the trailer. Driver immediately pulled off road and local regulatory agencies were called to the scene. Marion Environmental was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Upon inspection, Marion Environmental determined all 3 fallen totes had been compromised and approximately 76 gallons had been released to roadside soil. Marion Environmental proceeded to transfer the remaining product from the damaged totes to 3 recovery totes, excavated the impacted soil along shoulder, and containerized damaged totes and soil within one dump truck, which was transported off site for disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. All product was recovered, site was restored to preexisting condition, and no further action is planned. There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column170: The Way, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce driver safety and handling procedures to all personnel.

On February 14, 2025, a W2 Logistic, Inc tractor trailer was involved in a motor vehicle incident that resulted in a cargo release. The trailer was hauling various drums and totes of non-hazardous, non-regulated, and hazardous UN1760, Corrosive liquids. Approximately 300-500-gallons of various products released to the environment. Local authorities, Mike Lamb from Emergency Management & Homeland Security, and Deran’s Towing Service were on site.   Transportation Spill Solutions (TSS) reviewed the report from the Fire Department. According to the report, Mike Lamb and the Fire Department’s Hazmat Team conducted the initial cleanup of the release. The FD indicated that there (3) 55-gallon drums, (3) 250-gallon totes, and (2) 5-gallon buckets near the nose of the trailer. Only (2) 250-gallon totes and (1) 55-gallon drum was leaking inside the trailer. There were (4) 55-gallon drums and (1) 250-gallon tote outside the trailer. FD transferred material into (1) 55-gallon drum, (2) 95-gallon drums, (2) 65-gallon drums, and (1) 35-gallon drum. There was also a hydraulic oil release that was cleaned. All drums were labelled and staged on the side of the roadway.

On 2/24/25, at 15:22 hours, personnel in the CSXT Augusta, GA Yard discovered ENGX 200013, a tank car, residue: last contained Ammonium Nitrate, liquid leaking from the bottom outlet valve. The car was isolated and BASF Corporation were notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2025022400160). HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a small drip coming from the bottom outlet area. Contractor personnel were not able to stop the leak and therefor drained remaining residue from the tank car. Contractor personnel then washed the tank car to ensure no additional hazardous residue would leak. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (David White, 973-262-7591).

column43: SULFURIC ACID WITH NOT MORE THAN 51% ACID
column169: On February 19, 2025, at 1938 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar Ranger personnel in Denison, Texas regarding the release of Sulfuric Acid 50%. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 775 gallons of Sulfuric Acid 50% (UN2796, 8, II) from (3) 330-gallon plastic totes onto asphalt and an adjacent ditch. The release was reportedly due to a rollover accident, impacting multiple areas of asphalt and soil. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. The release was neutralized then cleaned with absorbents and the proper PPE. Removal of impacted soil is pending future remediation by contractors. All waste generated from the emergency response portion of addressing this release was containerized in (6) 55-gallon DFs which were taken onsite by contractors pending proper disposal.

column169: When our driver hooked up to the customer fill line and recognized when that the connection of the adapter fitting didn't feel snug enough (we teach drivers to do the twist test) so he used shims and that helped tigthen up the connection but when he started unloading product began spraying out.  By the time he shut down and the pressure relieved 1 gallon was lost amongst his bucket, spill pads and the ground which the customer helped clean up.  Additional shims and double gaskets weren't enough to overcome the problem.  After going through the troubleshooting we were able to deduce that the camlock arms on the fitting were bad and was going to need to be replaced altogether to make delivery.
column170: There was aspects on this delivery that required coaching but with respects to the spill and how it occurred we feel he was following the correct protocols.  We did need to get him replacement arms for that fitting as those are supposed to be in part of their repair kits.  I don't feel we need to change anything with respects to the training or processes that the driver followed.

On February 3, 2025, one (1) 330-gallon tote of phosphoric acid was punctured and released approximately 330-gallons of product to the asphalt pavement and nearby storm drain. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. TLE personnel noted that the product released into a storm drain onsite and began utilizing a vacuum trailer to remove the liquids at each storm drain between the terminal building and the retention pond. All acid impacted liquids were collected and containerized into three (3) 330-gallon totes and one (1) 275-gallon tote and staged onsite for further management.

attachment Name:Hazmat- Damaged Haz Mat Package Disposition 04302024.pdf

On February 20, a Veolia employee was unloading a trailer at Veolia's Richmond facility. The employee removed a 275 gallon IBC tote from the trailer using a forklift and placed it on the ground. The employee then went to grab the next pallet, and as he was placing it down, he noticed a small stain of liquid on the ground underneath the tote. Upon noticing that liquid was dripping onto the ground, the employee grabbed absorbent pads and placed it around the tote to prevent the spill from spreading. Approximately two ounces of hazardous waste liquid spilled within the two minutes it took to control the spill. The material in the tote was transferred to another tote using a gravity feed. It was determined that the leak originated from the  bottom of the tote since there was no evidence of visible damage to any other part of the tote. However, since the tote was inside a cage, it was not possible to pinpoint the exact location of the hole on the bottom of the tote.
column170: Veolia will review this incident with all field service employees involved in handling hazardous material during the monthly safety meeting. Veolia employees who are involved in handling totes will be notified/trained to verify the integrity of totes. The integrity of all hazmat containers must be evaluated prior to handling to ensure that there are no deficiencies that can lead to a chemical release.

When driver was breaking down hose lines he was pulling vacuum to clear lines the pump began blowing material out of the exhaust of the pump. Driver was at the back of the trailer and did not notice it right away and when it was noticed the pump was shut down and absorbent wer put down to contain the material. The material was released onto pavement and no drains were affected. There was approximately 10 gallons released and a team was dispatched to perform the clean up. They were notified at 1545et and arrived at 1745et. Once they arrived they assessed the scene and began a plan for the clean up. PPE was dawned and the clean up began at 1830et. The material had frozen due to the extreme cold which helped prevent the material from spreading. The team used shovels and absorbents to collect the material and dispose of in the proper containers. The clean up was completed at 2030et.
column170: It was is believed that water in the material froxxse in the check valve in the exhaust of the pump due to the extreme cold preventing the check valve from closing preventing the material from escaping. The driver in the future will keep a close eye on the pump during extreme cold when breaking down.

column169: On 02-25-2025 the CN Dangerous Goods Team was notified by a CN Mechanical employee regarding a strong chemical odor coming from tank car SHQX 51073. Car is in the CN Kirk Yard in Gary, IN. The employee notified the Mechanical Supervisor who then initiated an emergency response from the CN Dangerous Goods Team.  The CN Dangerous Goods Officer and Emergency response contractor upon arrival and inspection found icing on the 2# A end liquid valve. It was found that the valve handle was not in the fully closed position. The plug was also found to be less than tool tight allowing product to leak out.  The 2" A end liquid valve was closed stopping the release. The plug was loosened allowing the residual product to vent and the valve to thaw. The securement was confirmed with an air monitor which showed non detect. The securement plug was then installed.

Driver went to fill 6,800 gallon tank, and gauge said that it had room for 4,000 gallons. He knew he had just under 4,000 on his truck, but was not going to try to force it in. He stopped to blow out the lines just before the gauge hit 400 gallons left but it started to overflow. He had a loss of containment of about 30 gallons of ferric chloride by the time he blew out his lines. 100% went into containment. When he was done, the tank still read it had 400 gallons until full, indicating that the customer's tank gauge was not working properly. No Exposure Injuries.

column169: Veolia employees discovered a leaking 5-gallon carboy when they arrived at the customer location. The 5-gallon carboy was loaded at the previous pick up. Upon locating the leaking container, the employees discovered a screw was lodged in the carboy. The screw appeared to come from a loose panel in the back of the truck. A Veolia employee cleaned up the spill and notified Veolia EH&S.  The hole was in the side of the jerrican facing the wall of the truck. A loose board had two screws sticking out of it. One the the screws punctured the jerrican and caused a leak.  Duration of the release was about 15 minutes. A little less than half the contents leaked out of the jerrican.  Employees overpacked the jerrican into another container and cleaned up the liquid that spilled inside the truck.
column170: Veolia employees will be retrained to check cargo areas for any defects such as loose bolts prior to loading waste into vehicles. The truck panel was subsequently fixed by the Veolia employees. The panel will be rechecked after being put back into service.

Upon receiving a trailer, at Veolia's facility in Henderson, CO, a white powder was discovered.  The trailer was unloaded, and a tote of sodium bisulfite was found to be missing a bung, which is the suspected source of the powder. The chemical vaporized and reacted with metallic components in the trailer resulting in the powder covered the trailer floor, walls, ceiling, and the top of containers. The container was closed properly and received at the facility.
column170: Veolia field employees will be reminded to complete the Veolia Hazmat Checklist prior to transporting hazardous materials on a public roadway. The checklist contains reminders regarding compliance items such as, proper closure, segregation, load securement, placards, etc.

column169: HAZMAT PKG DISCOVERED IN THE LOAD. DECISION TREE   FLAMMABLE RESPONSE UTILIZED.

At 09:56 ET, XPO notified the Call Center of a cargo release at terminal LDA. It was reported that approximately 1 ounce of Rocryl 410 released from one 55-gallon metal drum due to the lid being improperly secured. The release impacted trailer #3214168. Call Center reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined that terminal personnel are capable of cleaning the release with PPE available on site. Waste label 228771-1 was created, one 95-gallon poly drum containing Oil Dri and one 55-gallon metal drum containing leftover product. CHEMTREC was notified of the release, report #2025022600087 was given by Charlie.  The waste was staged for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: Forklift strike

Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 2 feet by 2 feet area of concrete terminal floor and estimated that one (1) gallon of material was released due to a forklift accident puncturing one (1) 275-gallon plastic tote. Clean Harbors personnel stated that absorbents had been applied, and a neutralizer was used to the affected concrete area. The personnel then began a tote transfer from the punctured tote to a new tote. The old tote was cut up and placed in two (2) 55-gallon poly drums along with the impacted absorbents. The two (2) 55-gallon poly drums were staged onsite at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilization. Personnel were told the 330-gallon tote of product would be shipped on to the customer. The generated waste will remain onsite for the Dayton Freight Lines team to coordinate disposal.

At 1912 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal XCN. It was reported that approximately 100 gallons of "Aluminum Chloride Solution" were released from a plastic tote due to improper loading. The release impacted the inside of trailer #3115138. Per review of photos, this spill also impacted a drain and concrete under the trailer. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined that terminal personnel are not capable of cleaning the release with PPE available on site. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 110-gallons of UN2581 Aluminum Chloride Solution product released impacting 1’x40’ drain, 12’x8’ concrete and 5’x12’ trailer floor due to improper loading. The crew recovered the Aluminum Chloride Solution with absorbents and transferred the remaining product into a new tote and cut up damaged tote. The waste consisted of (5) 55-gallon poly totes containing the Aluminum Chloride Solution impacted boom, pads and oil dry, one drum had the impacted cut up tote. The waste was  staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

At 1519 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at XNW. It was reported that approximately 1 gallon of Oxonia Active released from 5-gallon poly pail due to improper loading. The release impacted ITSB-0070. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined that terminal personnel are not capable of cleaning the release with PPE available on site. (Haz Class 5.2) No storm drains or waterways are reported to be impacted by the release.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-gallons of UN3109 Oxonia Active product released to an 2’ x3’ area of the trailer floor due to freight not being secured while in transit. The area impacted by oxidizer material was neutralized using Sodium Metabisulfite and areas neutral. The crew used Soda Ash to neutralize the pH. The team observed a pallet with an excavator arm which was also moderately impacted by the spill and  neutralized as best as possible. The waste consisted of pails of product was containerized into (1) 55- gallon poly drum, waste product, soda ask, sodium metabisulfite, impacted wood, damaged pail and  water was put into (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

t 0415 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at XAN. It was reported that approximately 100 gallons of Enviroset 40E FNB Resin were released from a 275-gallon plastic tote due to improper loading by XAN. The release impacted trailer #4413259 and the concrete outside the trailer. ERTS will proceed to dispatch a contractor to the site to complete cleanup activities.   Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 200-gallons of UN2874 Enviroset 40E FNB Resin product released to the entire wooden trailer floor and the concrete beneath the trailer which spread to nine trailer bays, as well as sewer drain was impacted. The contractor applied speedy dry to the release that impacted the concrete and placed booms around the drains as well as the outfall. The estimated 10-gallons still in the tote was solidified with speedy dry and the tote were placed in a roll off for disposal. The contractors flushed the impacted sewer drain and vacuumed and filled (3) totes with impacted water/product. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: One 02/25/2025, at approximately 12:30 hours, an FRA inspector at the CSX Frontier Yard in Buffalo NY, discovered tank car PROX 35916, load of Liquefied Petroleum Gas, was leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Marathon Petroleum Company, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2025-02-25-00146). EnviroServe, a CSX  emergency response contractor, responded and found the cause of the release was the tank car’s liquid line valve was partially open, and  secondary closure plug was less than tool tight. Contractor personnel secured the car and verified the release was stopped. The issue identified, and corrective actions, were communicated to the shipper’s representative-John Andersen.

1. E-2025020358 On February 14, 2025, a W2 Logistic, Inc tractor trailer was involved in a motor vehicle incident that resulted in a cargo release. The trailer was hauling various drums and totes of non-hazardous, non-regulated, and hazardous UN1760, Corrosive liquids. Approximately 300-500-gallons of various products released to the environment. Local authorities, Mike Lamb from Emergency Management & Homeland Security, and Deran’s Towing Service were on site. Transportation Spill Solutions (TSS) reviewed the report from the Fire Department. According to the report, Mike Lamb and the Fire Department’s Hazmat Team conducted the initial cleanup of the release. The FD indicated that there (3) 55-gallon drums, (3) 250-gallon totes, and (2) 5-gallon buckets near the nose of the trailer. Only (2) 250-gallon totes and (1) 55-gallon drum was leaking inside the trailer. There were (4) 55-gallon drums and (1) 250-gallon tote outside the trailer. FD transferred material into (1) 55-gallon drum, (2) 95-gallon drums, (2) 65-gallon drums, and (1) 35-gallon drum. There was also a hydraulic oil release that was cleaned. All drums were labelled and staged on the side of the roadway.   2. On February 15th, 2025, at 18:00 hours, personnel in the CSXT Montgomery, Alabama Yard discovered GATX 53808, a loaded tank car of Terpene Hydrocarbons NOS, leaking from the manway. The car was isolated and the shipper, Kraton Chemicals, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 20250215-00065). Marion Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the manway cover gasket improperly installed- allowing product to release from the car. Contractor personnel replaced the manway cover gasket and decontaminated the exterior of the car. Following securement of the car it was released for transportation.  The issues identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Gerri Sage).

column170: It was determined that the pallet was not in good enough shape to handle the amount of weight that is place on there from batteries. They will be using better pallets and when moving around with the fork lift they will be paying better attention as to how the pallet is holding up.

GES personnel transferred the product from the damaged 275-gallon tote to a new 275-gallon tote for further shipment by the terminal. column169: AT THE UPS FACILITY IN COLOGNE, GERMANY, ONE AIR PACKAGE FROM USA TO GERMANY WAS FOUND SOILED WITH A VERY STRONG ODOR. THE PACKAGE HAS AN EXCEPTED QUANTITY MARK APPLIED TO THE PACKAGE WITH CLASSES INDICATED AS 3, 4.1, 6.1, 8, AND 9.  CONTENT INSPECTION REVEALS MULTIPLE GLASS BOTTLES INSIDE WITH SEVERAL SHATTERED AND LEAKING. SEVEN GLASS BOTTLES ARE 500 ML SIZE EACH. SIXTEEN GLASS BOTTLES ARE 30 ML EACH. THE REGULATED CONTENTS INSIDE THE BOX ARE EXCEPTED QUANTITIES OF MATERIALS CLASSIFIED AS UN2874, FURFURYL ALCOHOL, 6.1, PG III, UN3265 CORROSIVE LIQUID ACIDIC ORGANOS NOS, CLASS 8, PG III, UN1224 KETONES LIQUID NOS, CLASS 3, PG III, UN1325 FLAMMABLE SOLIDS ORGANIC NOS, CLASS 4.1, PG III, AND UN1197 EXTRACTS FLAVORING LIQUID, CLASS 3, PG II.  THERE ARE ADDITIONAL CHEMICALS INSIDE THE BOX THAT ARE NOT REGULATED IN TRANSPORTATION. THE PACKAGE AND CONTENTS WILL BE DISPOSED OF.

column169: On 02/04/2025, at 14:20 hours, personnel in the CSXT Hawthorne Yard in Indianapolis, Indiana, discovered UTLX632003, tank car load of Sodium Hydroxide Solution, had residue adhering to the outside of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Shintech Louisiana LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2025-0204-00181). HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and observed dried residue on the exterior of the car which appeared to have released from the tank car’s pressure relief valve. No active leaks or apparent defects were observed.  HEPACO personnel decontaminated the exterior of the tank car.  All actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Patrick Hill). The car was initially held at FRA’s request and subsequently moved under authority of an OTMA-1 (FRA-250213014).

column169: While working in the warehouse at Veolia's ten-day in-transit facility in Arlington, TX, a Veolia employee accidentally knocked over 6 containers that were stacked on top of other containers on a pallet. Trained Veolia employees immediately righted the containers and remediated the release of material using absorbent material on top of the spill. The container was uprighted and the lid was re-secured to the package.

Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, they observed an estimated (150) gallons of material released from one (1) 330-gallon plastic tote punctured by a forklift. Clean Harbors personnel observed that the released material impacted 30 ft-by-30 ft area of dock floor concrete. Clean Harbors personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and containerized them into three (3) 55-gallon poly drums. The remaining material in the product tote was to be transferred to a new 330-gallon IBC tote. However, both pumps cleaned harbors brought were faulty. They had obtained a functional pump from a local supplier and began pumping out the material. Work was paused to obtain upgraded PPE. After obtaining the correct PPE, personnel were able to complete the tote transfer. The incident generated a total of six (6) containers. One (1) 55-gallon poly drum contains two (2) 330-gallon poly tote bladders (cut up), Poly sheeting, and PPE. One (1) 55-gallon poly drum contains a diaphragm pump rinse water. One (1) 330-gallon tote contains the original product. Three (3) 55-gallon poly drums contain absorbent debris. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

The shipment was placed into a steel salvage package and a new declaration will be obtained for movement.

XPO-XNW contacted ERTS regarding a leaking 55-gallon DF containing hazardous product, VORTEXX. A  contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 5-gallons of product released onto the wooden trailer floor in  a 4’x4’ area as a result of improper loading. The contractor applied simple green to the release and  overpacked the leaking drum into one 95-gallon DF for waste disposal. The impacted absorbent pads and PPE  were containerized into a separate drum for waste disposal. XPO will manage all waste created from the spill  response. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.

On 02/25/2025 hidden dangerous goods were discovered during the shipment inspection process at the DHL CLE Service Center, 19987 Commerce Parkway, Middleburg Heights, OH 44130 Transportation by road confirmed.

Driver was traveling about 7 mph while attempting to make a U-turn on a remote road. Tires on passenger side of trailer entered soft shoulder causing trailer to roll. There were no 3rd parties, no injuries, and some damage to barbwire fence and street sign. Crisis Center was notified and activated. Local Vehicle Recovery Teams from Galt and Santa Clara have responded to the scene. Local fire department responded to scene. Corporate Safety and Environmental notified. Our Air Products driver arrived at the scheduled delivery location with a fully loaded Nitrogen trailer when he approached a gate. The driver exited his vehicle and quickly determined he was at the wrong location. Upon returning to his vehicle, he decided to perform a U-Turn on a narrow two-lane road which had an incline. During the maneuvering, the back end of the trailer dug into soft shoulder and mud, the weight of the trailer pushed the tractor which caused the trailer to break away from the 5th wheel and roll against the tractor. The trailer then rolled over onto its side across the roadway. The trailer released liquid Nitrogen due to the PSV line being damaged. During the roll over event, the tractor’s fuel tank was ruptured causing a diesel spill onto the ground. There were no injuries reported, and no other vehicles involved in this incident.
column170: Provide further focused training on basic procedures and what to do in critical situations. Including, but not limited to, proper trip planning. Thoroughly review route directions and instructions for the customer. Asking for help if you've never been to customer before. Reminders for drivers to call their supervisor when unsure what to do in any situation.

This is a customer unload. After arriving at the plant, the driver sits in his Tractor while the customer unloads the trailer. After the customer hooked up, they began to offload with a 3'' pump. Approximately 1 hour into the unloading cycle, the trailer suffered a vaccum collapse. It was determined that the customer failed to ensure that a ball valve was open on their vapor recovery line. Approximately 2000 gallons of HCL spilled from the bottom of the trailer During the event. All but 100-200 gallons was caught in their containment area. The remaining material left containment and leaked onto a gravel area leading to the unloading area. 1800 gallons inside containment was pumped into totes, and the material that left containment in a gravel area was neutralized and then disposed of by plant personnel. The trailer will be totaled by our insurance company.
column170: We are working on revamping unloading procedures and developing offloading checklists with our shipper and customers.

Truck driver lost control of vehicle, struck cement barrier on side of roadway. Driver over corrected causing the trailer to sway, then rollover. Unit remained on roadway and no other vehicles were involved. This trailer consisted of 4 compartments. The last compartment received a puncture spilling 2,000 gals. of ULSD B2. The product ran down the roadway and entered storm drains that discharged rain fall into Pine Creek. Pine Creek discharges into The Allegheny River approximately 1 /2 mile downstream from the spill. The duration of the release was immediate & flowed freely until fire department was on scene. The trailer was an aluminum MC 306 built by Custom in the year 1995.  Multiple fire departments were on scene along with the PA State Police, Allegheny County Hazmat, Etna Baro Police and others. On initial impact a fire started from product spilled along the barrier wall when contacted and ruptured. The fire department extinguished with no incident. The driver exited from the cab on his own, transported to ER and released with no injuries other than a cut on his hand. The fire departments blocked the drains with booms and other material to stop any continuous flow that could occur. A HM Spill Contractor was called to remove the remaining ULSD from the other 3 compartments. The trailer needed to be drilled to install a pump out hose into the tank. Product was transferred without further incident. The contractor was completing cleanup while the action of pumping the trailer was done. After the truck was righted and removed from the scene under tow, the contractor continued with the cleanup under the supervision of the PennDOT responder. Fire crews installed booms in the creek and at the mouth where the creek empties into the Allegheny River. The creek and river are an ongoing project to retain and remove product. Multiple state and local agencies are involved in monitoring the spill cleanup actions.
column170: The steps we are taking to prevent this type of incident are immediate. First, we have been in business for over 50 years, and we take any incident very seriously. In this case, I have notified the whole company via email to all terminals and to all drivers via their ELD messaging system. The Risk department is currently showing the video of this incident to all drivers face to face. The video is already having a major impact on our drivers that have watched the video. We are focused and committed on specialized training to establish a completely safe culture. In this case, reinforcing the importance of distraction free driving. We recognize that most preventable incidents are due to human error and an;? not mechanical errors. We have immediately increased our drivers' observations. Our Lead Driver Trainers will also use this incident to talk about distracted driving during training .

A 16-gallon DF containing impacted pallet pieces was generated for waste disposal. XPO will manage all the waste created from the response. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.

column169: On February 6, 2025, an incident occurred during a routine loading operation by a Veolia employee. While transferring containers onto a truck, the worker utilized a drum dolly to transport a 55-gallon polyethylene drum. Upon setting the drum down inside the vehicle, the employee observed approximately one pint of clear liquid pooling around the drum's base.  Further inspection revealed a small hole at the bottom of the drum, which was the source of the leak. To contain and manage the spill, the worker promptly employed vermiculite and absorbent pads. These materials effectively prevented the liquid from spreading and facilitated the cleanup process.  To ensure safe transportation to the intended facility, the compromised drum was placed inside an overpack container. This additional precaution allowed for the secure continuation of the drum's journey to its final destination.
column170: Veolia will review this incident with employees to remind them to inspect the condition of all containers prior to moving them and to be aware of the force used when setting down a drum on a drum dolly.

column169: On February 6, 2025, at 0821 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar Inway personnel in Helena, AR regarding the release of Vydate C-LV. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of approximately 25.0 gallons of Vydate C-LV (UN2991, 6.1 (3), II) from (1) 275-gal poly tote onto the trailer floor and asphalt. The release was reportedly due to the tote’s securement strap gouging the top of the poly tote bladder causing a release in transit, impacting multiple areas of the trailer floor and asphalt. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. The release was cleaned up with absorbents and the proper PPE. Contractors transferred the remaining product from the damaged tote to a new tote to continue on to the consignee. The damaged tote was shredded and containerized by the contractors. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (2) 55-gallon DF which were left offsite by the contractor for proper disposal.

column169: John Ognibene, 026 Operation Supervisor, contacted Safety regarding a UN3265 corrosive liquid spill on the trailer and dock floor. John Ognibene advised he noticed the spill while walking the dock. John Ognibene stated it's unknown if any of the commodity struck the yard due to it being dark and the  product being clear. John Ognibene advised both sides of the drum are caved in but is unknown if that's what caused the spill. John Ognibene stated the drum is still leaking so he moved the drum off the trailer, down the dock by the dumpster to be out of the way of workers. John Ognibene asked if h e could place wood chips over the spill and Safety advised yes to can contain the spill. Safety contacted Mattisyn Keys with Cura for remediation. ~~Safety advised Mattisyn Keys to advise Safety if any struck the yard and if the spill becomes reportable. Safety also requested the cause of the spill.  ~~Update from Cura- "It took some time to get a contractor to respond earlier this morning. The crew just wrapped up at the terminal, completing removal of the environmental concern. The drums looked to have been compressed inside the trailer, causing the release. I am not finding any ingredients o n this product to be reportable."

column169: Unload managers noticed that a plastic bubble-mailer envelope recently placed on the IC belt in the unload was smoking. A manager ripped it open and found that the package contained six boxes of safety matches. One of the boxes had caught on fire. The manager blew out the fire and alerted the DG Nav specialist, who was in the middle of processing hazmats. DG Nav specialist isolated the damaged package on a metal rack where it could not spread fire if it were to catch on fire again. The matches in the one box appear to be mostly or fully "used" given the burnt appearance. The other five boxes are in acceptable condition.

column169: On February 20, 2025, at 1817 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar Inway personnel in Sulphur Springs, TX regarding the release of Dynasylan® SILBOND® 40. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 35.0 gallons of Dynasylan® SILBOND® 40 (UN1993, 3, III) from (1) 55-gallon metal drum onto the trailer floor and asphalt. The release was reportedly due to a load shift, impacting (4) wooden pallets on the trailer floor and a 3’ x 3’ area of asphalt. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. Contractors found that the release was evaporated by the time they arrived on site. With the proper PPE, contractors removed the (1) leaking drum and placed it into an overpack, then removed (5) damaged drums from the pallets to be reviewed by the client for disposition. Impacted pallets and plastic were broken up and containerized. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (3) 55-gallon DFs and (1) 85-gallon poly overpack which were taken onsite by contractors for proper disposal.

column169: DURING NORMAL UNLOADING PROCESS ONE AIR PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING A DARK LIQUID. AN EMPLOYEE WAS EXPOSED TO THE UNKNOWN DARK LIQUID CAUSING A NEGATIVE REACTION. THE SUBSTANCE BEGAN EATING AWAY THE SHIRT AND A BURNING SENSATION WAS FELT ON THEIR ABDOMEN AREA. ONSITE IMMEDIATE ACTION WAS TAKEN TO REMOVE THEIR SHIRT AND WASH THE AFFECTED AREA. EMPLOYEE WAS THEN TREATED AT A LOCAL CLINIC AND RELEASED. RESPONDER INSPECTED PACKAGE CONTENTS TO FIND FOUR X ONE LITER JUGS OF CORROSIVE HERCULES CLOBBER EMERGENCY DRAIN OPENER. ONE OF THE CONTAINERS WAS LEAKING FROM THE CLOSURE. THERE ARE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER BOX TO INDICATE A REGULATED DANGEROUS GOODS WAS BEING SHIPPED IN THE AIR NETWORK. THIS PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED FROM TEXAS USING UPS ACCOUNT NUMBER K1012B, CORPUS WAREHOUSE, 2050 SARATOGA BLVD, CORPUS CHRISTI TX 78417-3403.THIS PACKAGE HAS NOT BEEN ACCEPTED FOR AIR OR TRANSPORTED IN THE AIR BY UNITED PARCEL SERVICE CO.
